popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Dafydd ap Ieuan was born about 1287, in Llanbadarn-odwyn, Cardiganshire, Wales, his father, Ieuan ap Gruffudd, was 29 and his mother, Ellyw Angharad ferch Maredudd, was 28. He had at least 1 daughter with Mrs. Dafydd ap Ieuan."},"et":{"about 1287–":"umbes 1287–Surnud","1285–Male":"1285–Surnud","1287–Male":"1287–Surnud","1290–Male":"1290–Surnud","1298–Male":"1298–Surnud","1300–1392":"1300–1392","1450–1502":"1450–1502","1290–Female":"1290–Surnud","1312–Female":"1312–Surnud","1260–1359":"1260–1359","1260–1332":"1260–1332","1285":"1285","1450":"1450","1260":"1260","1392":"1392","1290":"1290","1359":"1359","1502":"1502","1312":"1312","1300":"1300","1332":"1332","1